title: For Sale:  BEWARE OF WTB AD'S
postcontent:
WHEN YOU SEE A WTB AD ON ARMSLIST FOR AMMO, ESPECIALLY WHEN THEY ARE WANTING IF FOR PRE PANIC OR CHEAP PRICES YOU SHOULD ALWAYS CHECK OUT THE LISTINGS BY USER ON THEIR AD. THIS LINK WILL SHOW IF THIS PERSON HAS OTHER AD'S UP. IN THE PAST FEW YEARS I HAVE FIRST HANDED WITNESSED DOZENS OF PEOPLE POSTING AD'S SELLING AMMO AT A HIGH PREMIUM AND THAN ALSO TURNING AROUND TO POST A WTB AD FOR AMMO AT A CHEAP REASONABLE PRICE CLAIMING THAT THEY CANT FIND ANY OR ITS UNFAIR THAT PEOPLE ARE ASKING MORE THAN WHAT THEY WANT TO PAY.

THERE IS A LOT OF DECENT PEOPLE WHO ARE WILLING TO SELL A COUPLE BOX'S OF THEIR PERSONAL STASH SO A FELLOW SHOOTER CAN GO PUT ROUNDS DOWN RANGE, BUT THERE ARE THESE PEOPLE WHO JUST BUY THOSE ROUNDS AND THEN TURN AROUND TO MARK UP THE PRICE JUST TO SELL IT...

I purchased this Sig in 2008 and it has performed flawlessly.  There are probably about 500 rounds through the gun, and to date I have not experienced a single issue of any kind. *Extended Beavertail - Great feature to keep your hands safe from slide or hammer bite!

*Slide serrations on both the front and rear of the slide
*Short Reset Trigger - Sig's proprietary Short Reset Trigger (SRT) allows faster follow up shots, a lighter single action trigger pull, and very little trigger travel.  This is one of my favorite features on the gun personally.
*Rosewood Grips - These were from early 2008, right before the big gun rush.  Shortly thereafter Sig stopped making the 226 elite with the rosewood grips because they couldn't get a hold of enough good wood to keep up with demand.  
*Front rail - great for any accessories you may want to attach (lights, etc) - great feature for a duty or home defense weapon.

Condition:
I had a gun shop look over the gun to give me an estimate of condition, and their appraisal was "at least 99% perfect".  I've tried to get close up shots to show the condition.  The wood grips are in perfect shape, I can't find any marks, gouges, or scratches.  The finish on the metal is also in extremely good condition, with no marks or scratches.  The only place where wear-from-use is noticed is on the barrel itself, where you'd see the typical stainless finish starting to peek through the black.

I'm more than happy to answer any questions you may have, email is the best way to get a hold of me. The SPAS 12 was designed to function primarily as a semi-automatic firearm, with the pump-action mode used to reliably fire low-pressure ammunition such as tear gas rounds or less-lethal bean bags. The firing mode is switched by pressing a button under the fore grip and sliding the fore grip slightly forwards or backwards until it clicks into position.
The SPAS-12 has a magazine cut-off feature, which prevents loading a new round from the internal magazine when the gun is cycled. This hook could be rotated in 90-degree increments, so it would fit under the user's forearm when the stock was extended. postcontent:
This is a PTR-91 (HK91 clone) in very good condition, it is an early version with many HK91 parts on it. Armslist doesn't offer me the choice to list "PTR industries" as the manufacturer, so I listed it as HK, but THIS rifle for sale is actually the PTR-91. 
It shoots very well, has a removable picatinny rail on it (see picture), removable bipod, flash hider, and seventeen (17) 20-round magazines, many of which are HK brand. Awesome reliable battle rifle, I love it but it never did fit me quite right. I am in no hurry to sell it, though, I will only answer serious inquiries.  text me at 918-928-634-four

More information on the rifle: 
The weapon is based on the Heckler & Koch G3/HK91 design widely used around the world, which itself is a variant of the Spanish-made CETME rifle. The United States Federal assault weapons ban of 1994 (which expired in 2004) prohibited certain cosmetic features of the HK91, meaning that it could no longer be manufactured and sold to the US civilian market in its original configuration. Furthermore, the German-made HK91 was specifically prohibited from importation under the US 1989 Import Ban. Subsequently Heckler and Koch ceased manufacture of the semi-automatic HK91, and since then civilian versions of the G3 have increased in collector value. The PTR-91 was developed to fill the void, as the two rifles are almost identical.
JLD Enterprises ("JLD") began manufacturing ban compliant PTR-91 rifles in 2002, after purchasing prints and tooling from Fabrica Militar of Portugal - an HK licensed factory. The ban compliant models did not have a threaded barrel, bayonet lugs, adjustable stocks, or "high capacity" magazines. Very early models, being produced directly from the purchased prints were nearly identical to the HK91 with the exception of modifications for compliance with the assault weapons ban. After the ban's expiration in 2004, JLD began offering a wider range of PTR-91 models, many of which featured more of the original military features. JLD also began investing in research and development, and debuted many new improvements and modifications to the original HK91 design. Initially, JLD produced rifles relied heavily on imported military surplus components for G3/HK91 rifles. In fact, most parts between the HK-91 and the PTR-91 are interchangeable.
In 2005, the major assets of JLD Enterprises were purchased by the newly formed PTR-91 Inc. Mr. Jose Diaz (JLD Enterprises' founder and owner) stayed on with the new company as a major partner. Mr. Diaz left the company in late 2010. Subsequently, the remaining partners and new management changed the strategic direction of the company. PTR moved from a business model of surplus part importation and assembly, to that of a true manufacturer - physically producing the components of the weapon in house. The company added significant machining and fabrication capabilities over the course of 2011 and 2012 to accomplish this change. Currently PTR is capable of producing every machined part on the rifles at its own plant in Bristol, CT - and sources other items (plastic, etc...) locally in the United States on tooling that it owns and produced. As a result, the current PTR rifles are actually made in the U.S. rather than simply assembled in the U.S. In order to represent the change in direction and capability of the business - the company recently adopted its current name, PTR Industries, Inc.
In the summer of 2013 PTR relocated to Aynor, South Carolina due in part to increasing gun control laws in Connecticut.
Today the company offers more than 25 different model variations, and has expanded into the law enforcement and military markets as well.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Enfield 2A Ishapore 7.62 NATO
location: Saint Paul, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Now you too can own the "Last Bolt Action Battle Rifle". Yes, you heard that correctly.

Up for sale only, no trades. Enfield 2A "Ishapore" - the "Last Bolt Action Battle Rifle" manufactured in 1964 at "RFI" (Rifle Factory Ishapore) in India, chambered in 7.62mm NATO.

The Indians wanted a rifle that was chambered in a standard NATO round (due to ammunition availability) so they took the Enfield technology (found in the 1mkIII) and adapted it to a brand new rifle, chambered in 7.62 NATO (aka. .308 Winchester). Who cares that the rest of the world had been using automatics since WWII....India wanted BOLT ACTION (I mean cmon rest of the world, ammo's expensive).

This rifle is in phenomenal shape considering its journey, probably into the Himalayas...I mean the Indians don't like the Pakistanis or the Chinese, so its probably even fired a shot or two in anger...but probably not...I mean really, would you bring a bolt action into combat these days? 

It is import marked on the receiver. Strong bore and rifling....no rust anywhere which is shocking seeing as how its really fricken humid over there, and gun maintenance isn't generally high on the list of priorities. This one has been cleaned of the slapdash black paint that was on many of the imports. Wood is in great shape, with a few well done arsenal repairs to the stock heel. These stocks were prone to cracking, so they did pre-emptive maintenance on many to strengthen this area. Honest dents and dings in a few areas...but it was a battle rifle...and it may or may not have been around the block a few times.

I've had it out to the range twice since I've owned it -- its a great shooter. I've seen alot of these sporterized, but I just couldn't bring myself to put a scope on it....call me old-fashioned.

Comes with....a rifle, enfield sling and a 100rds of .308 (dealer's choice on bullet weight - it seems to like the expensive stuff....but lets be honest, who doesn't? ‪#‎amiright‬?)

$275 OBO (cash or card +3%). ("Best Offer" is usually one that isn't half what I'm asking, doesn't involve anything made by Jennings, and doesn't require me to drive 3/4's of the way to International Falls... I can look on gunbroker just like you can...and this thing doesn't eat anything or make me change the channel so it can watch it's show...just sayin'...I HAVE seen something else shiny that interested me however).

I'm in Saint Paul and Anoka daily. I'll need a glance at your MN ID and PTP/PTC also. Will not ship.
